Exercise 01

?datasaurus_dozen

There are 1846 observational units and 3 variables in the dataset datasauraus_dozen.

The variables which are included in the dataset are as follows -

dataset - tells us from which dataset are the data from

x gives us the x values

y gives us the y values

Frequency table of the dataset

datasaurus_dozen %>%
  count(dataset) %>%
  print(13)

Exercise 02

dino_data<-datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset=="dino")
ggplot(data = dino_data,mapping = aes(x=x,y=y)) +
  geom_point()

Correlation Coefficient

dino_data %>%
  summarize(r=cor(x,y))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0645

Exercise 3

star_data<-datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset=="star")
ggplot(data = star_data,mapping = aes(x=x,y=y))+
  geom_point()

star_data %>%
  summarize(r=cor(x,y))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0630

This value is lesser to the correlation of the dino dataset.

Exercise 4

circle_data<-datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset=="circle")
ggplot(data = circle_data,mapping = aes(x=x,y=y))+geom_point()

circle_data %>%
  summarize(r=cor(x,y))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0683

This is value is greater lesser the correlation coefficient obtained in the dino dataset.

Exercise 5

ggplot(data = datasaurus_dozen,mapping = aes(x=x,y=y,col = dataset))+
  geom_point()+
  facet_wrap(~dataset,ncol = 3)+
  theme(legend.position = "none")

datasaurus_dozen %>%
  group_by(dataset)%>%
  summarize(r = cor(x,y))
## # A tibble: 13 x 2
